{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"82edcc1f-6750-433c-8a85-832e9584c654","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from your .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Exec into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace`:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n$env:PATH += \";C:\\Users\\ContainerUser\\.dotnet\\tools\"\n```\n\n**3. Find your process:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect a CPU trace (30s example):**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**5. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace.nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**6. Analyze** with Visual Studio (open the `.nettrace`), PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (convert first with `dotnet-trace convert`).\n\n**If `dotnet-trace` can't attach** (common in some container images), use the **event pipe** environment variable approach instead — set `DOTNET_EnableDiagnostics=1` and restart, or use `dotnet-counters monitor` first to confirm connectivity.\n\n**Alt: host-level capture** — since you have admin on the node, you can run PerfView or `xperf`/WPR directly on the host to capture system-wide ETW traces that include container processes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9bb40136-c495-42d7-8b59-caee59e608ce","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":461,"requestId":"1B80:75BF8:CCAA1A:E91D94:6A0280F6"},"id":"e9ae4189-a4dc-4212-8578-9732fe21fde0","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:23:13.651Z","parentId":"25f00652-5e06-4148-818f-bdf3c86e286e"}
